[1
Date: Thu, 17 Dec 1998 11:42:08 +0100 (MET)
From: Jean Dupouy-Camet <dupouyca@imaginet.fr>

I have noticed that trichinellosis is henceforth banished from the list but
being quoted in the latest ProMED-mail report about trichinellosis in
France, I would add the following and final comments:
1. I discuss in a previous ProMED-mail posting (Trichinosis, testing of
horse meat - European Union) how horses could be infected. Contaminated
pork fed to the horse is a possibility but accidental ingestion of wild
rodents or small carnivores grounded up in hay could explain horse
infections by wild isolates of _Trichinella_. Such a possibility could
occur in Mustangs...
2. Carcasses imported from North America are not frozen but refrigerated.
Carcasses from North America were responsible for two important outbreaks
involving 431 & 538 cases in 1985 and 1993 (Ancelle T et al., Am J
Epidemiol 1988 ;127:1302-11 & Am J Trop Med Hyg 1998 ;59:615-9).
Therefore, banning importations from Eastern Europe would not totally
suppress the risk of a new outbreak.
3. Horse meat related trichinellosis is definitely an emerging disease in
France and Italy. No outbreaks were described before 1975, 5 outbreaks were
described between 1975 and 1985 and 8 outbreaks were described since 1985
(3 of them reported in 1998 and involving more than 600 cases).
4. The veterinary control of trichinellosis, compulsory since 1985, is
inaccurate and inefficient. This is particularly worrying since a
veterinary control could be suggested for BSE prevention. If finding one
millimetre larvae in meat samples appears so difficult, what about finding
prions? An efficient prevention of horse meat trichinellosis could
therefore be a good model for preventing BSE.
--
Pr Jean Dupouy-Camet (MD, PhD)
Member of The International Commission on Trichinellosis
Service de Parasitologie-Mycologie
