[2
Date: Wed, 16 Dec 1998 16:38:58 -0700
From: Dale Armstrong <dale.armstrong@agric.gov.ab.ca>

I am a food animal veterinarian in North America and went to school in NA
so my experience with the food safety of horse meat is virtually nil. I had
no idea that _Trichinella_ spp. were of concern in equine but that may be
my faulty memory cells after 25 years out of school. I am also a
pathologist and a Diplomate of the American College of Vet Pathology but
that is 12 years past and that also makes me rusty. I was very appreciative
to read the article on the outbreak in France and without it being on
ProMED-mail I would not have been so well informed. Alberta also has one of
the few horse processing plants in NA and the falling market prospects for
the product were also very enlightening.
_Trichinella_ spp. occur only in very isolated pockets in swine in NA and
if it occurred it would be a "big news" emerging disease within the whole
very sensitive area of food safety. This is particularly true now that pork
is developing diversified products with more emphasis on not over-cooking
pork (done traditionally for fear of _Trichinella_ spp. infestation).
Your comment that trichinellosis now be banished forever struck a cord of
fear that access to such information would be restricted on ProMED-mail,
which I have come to rely on for up-to-date health and food safety
information. Indicators of failures of inspection systems is extremely
important information to prevent negative public health occurrences and
even more important with our global agriculture trade environment that is
ever expanding. The numerous occurrences seen on your list from food
imports underscores that information need.
I would encourage you to reconsider your position on trichinellosis.
--
Dale Armstrong,
Alberta Agriculture Food and Rural Development,
Alberta,
Canada
[Amen. - MHJ
