[4
Date: Thu, 17 Dec 1998 12:11:55 -0500
From: Schantz, Peter M. <pms1@cdc.gov>

I would be inclined to argue that trichinellosis associated with horsemeat
consumption is indeed an emerging zoonosis. Horses are a relatively newly
recognized source and since 1974 there have been at least twelve outbreaks
totaling more than 2800 cases. Horsemeat has been ingested by the French
and Italians, among others, for generations but the new outbreaks are
presumably related to factors associated with the international economy,
such that infected carcasses are now reaching a vulnerable population
supported by diagnostic services capable of properly diagnosing the disease.
Another factor associated with re-emergence of trichinellosis is the
resurgence of the disease in many of the former SS Republics and some
Eastern European countries where the apparent breakdown in government and
social services, including reliable meat inspection, have conspired to
result in the acquisition of many thousand of cases of trichinellosis from
pork.
--
Peter M. Schantz, V.M.D., Ph.D
Division of Parasitic Diseases
National Center For Infectious Diseases
Centers For Disease Control and Prevention
Mailstop F22
4770 Buford Highway
Atlanta, GA 30341
e-mail: pms1@cdc.gov
